 captures the reality of those who are in the system, and those who are working to help them. Johnson offers a nuanced and compelling portrait of this fastest-growing prison population by blending legal history, ethnography, sociology, and criminology. These striking and vivid narratives are accompanied by equally compelling arguments by Johnson on how to reform our nation's laws and social policies, in order to eradicate existing inequalities. Her thorough and insightful analysis of the historical and legal background of contemporary criminal law doctrine, sentencing theories, and correctional policies sets the stage for understanding the current system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American prisonersvBiography. 0aAfrican American prisonersvInterviews. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 0aWomen prisonerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen prisonerszUnited StatesvInterviews. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican.  aAmerican.  aInner.  aLives.  aconnect.  aintimately.  aopportunity.  aprisoners.  aprovides.  arare.  areaders.  awith.  awomen.1 aDavis, Angela J.1 aDavis, Angela J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogan, Joyce A.1 aLogan, Joyce A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474254940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814743294.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814743294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814743294/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_